racters]]\n[[Category:Lists of American drama television series characters]]\n", "name_user": "IronMaximus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAppearances", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Black_Sails_characters"}
{"title_page": "Naval Photographic Science Laboratory", "text_new": "The United States '''Naval Photographic Science Laboratory''' was opened on 24 Feb 1943 at the Anacostia Naval Air Station, Washington, D. C., under the command of the Chief of the Bureau of Aeronautics. It was established to centralize the production and preservation of all Naval photography. \n\nThe Laboratory provided photographic services to the Navy and developed equipment and techniques suitable for fleet use. It was responsible for providing services and facilities for printing and developing films in quantity and for training motion picture cameramen. It was the Navy's major production unit for training films and undertook production work for any military or governmental activity when approved by the Bureau of Aeronautics. It maintained record copies of motion pictures made at the Laboratory and of still pictures sent in from naval air stations. \n\nIn 1947, it was renamed the Naval Photographic Center (NPC).\n", "text_old": "The United States Naval Photographic Science Laboratory was opened on 24 Feb 1943 at the Anacostia Naval Air Station, Washington, D. C., under the command of the Chief of the Bureau of Aeronautics. It was established to centralize the production and preservation of all Naval photography. \n\nThe Laboratory provided photographic services to the Navy and developed equipment and techniques suitable for fleet use. It was responsible for providing services and facilities for printing and developing films in quantity and for training motion picture cameramen. It was the Navy's major production unit for training films and undertook production work for any military or governmental activity when approved by the Bureau of Aeronautics. It maintained record copies of motion pictures made at the Laboratory and of still pictures sent in from naval air stations. \n\nIn 1947, it was renamed the Naval Photographic Center (NPC).\n", "name_user": "Bensci54", "label": "safe", "comment": "bolding subject", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naval_Photographic_Science_Laboratory"}
{"title_page": "Australia/Transportation", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Transport in Australia]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Transport in Australia]]\n\n{{R from CamelCase}}\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Australia/Transportation&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Plotius Grypus", "text_new": "'''Plotius Grypus''' was a partisan of the [[Roman empire|Roman]] emperor [[Vespasian]]. He was the brother of the [[urban prefect]] [[Plotius Pegasus]], and likely father of the identically named Plotius Grypus. The elder Grypus acceded to the [[Roman consul|suffect consulship]] for 13 January\u2013April 88, succeeding the emperor [[Domitian]].<ref>Paul Gallivan, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/638472 \"The Fasti for A. D. 70-96\"], ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', 31 (1981), pp. 191, 217</ref>\n\nWe are told by a scholiast on [[Juvenal]] that Grypus, like his brother Pegasus, were named by their father, an officer in the Roman navy, for ships he commanded.<ref>Edward Champlin, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/20185579 \"Pegasus\"], ''[[Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik]]'', 32 (1978), pp. 269f</ref> As an adult Grypus joined the military, and for siding with Vespasian during the strife of the [[Year of Four Emperors]], the victorious emperor [[adlecti|adlected]] him into the [[Roman senate]] late in the year 69.<ref>[[Tacitus]], ''[[Histories (Tacitus)|Histories]]'' 3.52</ref> Then in January 70 he replaced [[Tettius Julianus]] as [[praetor]], after Julianus was alleged to have deserted his post as [[Legatus|legate]] of his legion in [[Dacia]] when it had declared for Vespasian.<ref>Tacitus, ''Histories'', 4.39</ref> A few days afterwards the rank was restored to Tettius when he made it known that he had fled for refuge to Vespasian, but Grypus retained his rank.<ref>Tacitus, ''Histories'', 4.40</ref>\n\n[[Edward Champlin]] has identified as his son another Plotius Grypus, mentioned by [[Statius]] in one of the poems collected in his ''Silvae'' (IV.9), who was \"well launched on his senatorial career by the mid-90s\".<ref>Champlin, \"Pegasus\", p. 272</ref> This identification was accepted by Brian W. Jones, who notes that when Statius wrote his poem for the younger Grypus, he made no reference to his consular father. While admitting that the older Grypus may have died before the Sarmatian War{{which|date=November 2017}}, Jones suggests that a more likely reason may have been that by the time Statius wrote Grypus was in exile. The most likely reason for his exile would be as a result of the events of 70, when Tettius and Grypus struggled for the same praetorship, during which the old rivalry between the two revived, and so Tettius engineered Grypus' exile. \"In 88, though, the position was vastly different: Julianus was the hero of Tapae, victor over the Dacians, whereas it had taken Grypus 18 years to reach the consulship. Jealousy may have caused him to attempt to undermine his former rival, and failure led to his banishment.\"<ref>Jones, ''The Emperor Domitian'' (London: Routledge, 1993), p. 191</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Fran\u00e7ois Berard, [http://www.persee.fr/doc/mefr_0223-5102_1984_num_96_1_1409 \"La carri\u00e8re de Plotius Grypus et le ravitaillement de l'arm\u00e9e imp\u00e9riale en campagne\"], ''M\u00e9langes de l'\u00e9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome '', 96 (1984), pp. 259-324\n* [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]], [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/acl3129.0003.001/436 \"Plotius Griphus\"], in ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'' (1870), Vol. 3, p. 428\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Domitian]] XIV,<br/>and [[Lucius Minicius Rufus]]|as=Ordinary consuls}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of early imperial Roman consuls|Suffect consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] |years = 88 |regent1=[[Lucius Minicius Rufus]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Quintus Ninnius Hasta (consul 88)|Quintus Ninnius Hasta]],<br/>and [[Libo Rupilius Frugi|Lucius Scribonius Libo Rupilius Frugi Bonus]]|as=Suffect consuls}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Plotius Grypus}}\n\n[[Category:1st-century Romans]]\n[[Category:Imperial Roman praetors]]\n[[Category:Senators of the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Suffect consuls of Imperial Rome]]\n", "text_old": "'''Plotius Grypus''' was a partisan of the [[Roman empire|Roman]] emperor [[Vespasian]]. He was the brother of the [[urban prefect]] [[Plotius Pegasus]], and likely father of the identically named Plotius Grypus. The elder Grypus acceded to the [[Roman consul|suffect consulship]] for 13 January\u2013April 88, succeeding the emperor [[Domitian]].<ref>Paul Gallivan, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/638472 \"The Fasti for A. D. 70-96\"], ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', 31 (1981), pp. 191, 217</ref>\n\nWe are told by a scholiast on [[Juvenal]] that Grypus, like his brother Pegasus, were named by their father, an officer in the Roman navy, for ships he commanded.<ref>Edward Champlin, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/20185579 \"Pegasus\"], ''[[Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Papyrologie und Epigraphik]]'', 32 (1978), pp. 269f</ref> As an adult Grypus joined the military, and for siding with Vespasian during the strife of the [[Year of Four Emperors]], the victorious emperor [[adlecti|adlected]] him into the [[Roman senate]] late in the year 69.<ref>[[Tacitus]], ''[[Histories (Tacitus)|Histories]]'' 3.52</ref> Then in January 70 he replaced [[Tettius Julianus]] as [[praetor]], after Julianus was alleged to have deserted his post as [[Legatus|legate]] of his legion in [[Dacia]] when it had declared for Vespasian.<ref>Tacitus, ''Histories'', 4.39</ref> A few days afterwards the rank was restored to Tettius when he made it known that he had fled for refuge to Vespasian, but Grypus retained his rank.<ref>Tacitus, ''Histories'', 4.40</ref>\n\n[[Edward Champlin]] has identified as his son another Plotius Grypus, mentioned by [[Statius]] in one of the poems collected in his ''Silvae'' (IV.9), who was \"well launched on his senatorial career by the mid-90's\".<ref>Champlin, \"Pegasus\", p. 272</ref> This identification was accepted by Brian W. Jones, who notes that when Statius wrote his poem for the younger Grypus, he made no reference to his consular father. While admitting that the older Grypus may have died before the Sarmatian War{{which|date=November 2017}}, Jones suggests that a more likely reason may have been that by the time Statius wrote Grypus was in exile. The most likely reason for his exile would be as a result of the events of 70, when Tettius and Grypus struggled for the same praetorship, during which the old rivalry between the two revived, and so Tettius engineered Grypus' exile. \"In 88, though, the position was vastly different: Julianus was the hero of Tapae, victor over the Dacians, whereas it had taken Grypus 18 years to reach the consulship. Jealousy may have caused him to attempt to undermine his former rival, and failure led to his banishment.\"<ref>Jones, ''The Emperor Domitian'' (London: Routledge, 1993), p. 191</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Fran\u00e7ois Berard, [http://www.persee.fr/doc/mefr_0223-5102_1984_num_96_1_1409 \"La carri\u00e8re de Plotius Grypus et le ravitaillement de l'arm\u00e9e imp\u00e9riale en campagne\"], ''M\u00e9langes de l'\u00e9cole fran\u00e7aise de Rome '', 96 (1984), pp. 259-324\n* [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]], [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/m/moa/acl3129.0003.001/436 \"Plotius Griphus\"], in ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'' (1870), Vol. 3, p. 428\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Domitian]] XIV,<br/>and [[Lucius Minicius Rufus]]|as=Ordinary consuls}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of early imperial Roman consuls|Suffect consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]] |years = 88 |regent1=[[Lucius Minicius Rufus]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Quintus Ninnius Hasta (consul 88)|Quintus Ninnius Hasta]],<br/>and [[Libo Rupilius Frugi|Lucius Scribonius Libo Rupilius Frugi Bonus]]|as=Suffect consuls}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Plotius Grypus}}\n\n[[Category:1st-century Romans]]\n[[Category:Imperial Roman praetors]]\n[[Category:Senators of the Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:Suffect consuls of Imperial Rome]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plotius_Grypus"}
