/senior-doj-lawyer-donald-kempf-resigned-amid-misconduct-probe-sources-confirm/?cmp=share_twitter |title=Senior DOJ Lawyer Donald Kempf Resigned Amid Misconduct Probe, Sources Confirm |accessdate=February 9, 2018 |date=October 16, 2019 |work=[[National Law Journal]] |author=C. Ryan Barber |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221063753/https://www.law.com/nationallawjournal/2019/10/16/senior-doj-lawyer-donald-kempf-resigned-amid-misconduct-probe-sources-confirm/?cmp=share_twitter |archive-date=December 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[File:Seal of the United States Department of Justice.svg|70x70px]]<br>[[United States Attorney]]s\n| ''Various''\n| March 10, 2017\n| {{main|2017 dismissal of U.S. attorneys}}\nOn March 10, 2017, Attorney General [[Jeff Sessions]] requested the resignations of 46 [[United States Attorney]]s.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|title=Sessions asks 46 Obama-era U.S. attorneys to resign|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-justice-prosecutors-idUSKBN16H2K8|work=[[Reuters]]|date=March 10, 2017|first1=Joel|last1=Schechtman|first2=Mark|last2=Hosenball|accessdate=March 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310212501/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-justice-prosecutors-idUSKBN16H2K8|archive-date=March 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Trump declined to accept the resignations of [[Dana Boente]], who was serving as Acting Deputy Attorney General, and [[Rod Rosenstein]], whom Trump had selected to become Deputy Attorney General.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news|title=Bharara, Wall Street's Enforcer, Other Lawyers Asked to Quit|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-03-11/bharara-wall-street-s-enforcer-among-prosecutors-asked-to-quit|accessdate=March 10, 2017|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|website=Bloomberg.com|date=March 10, 2017|first1=Greg|last1=Farrell|first2=Christian|last2=Berthelsen|first3=Margaret|last3=Talev|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311020053/https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2017-03-11/bharara-wall-street-s-enforcer-among-prosecutors-asked-to-quit|archive-date=March 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Abruptly\">{{cite news|title=Trump Abruptly Orders 46 Obama-Era Prosecutors to Resign|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/10/us/politics/us-attorney-justice-department-trump.html|accessdate=March 10, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 10, 2017|first1=Charlie|last1=Savage|first2=Maggie|last2=Haberman|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|issn=0362-4331|oclc=1645522|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517002910/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/10/us/politics/us-attorney-justice-department-trump.html|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AG Sessions asks remaining 46 US attorneys to resign|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/03/10/ag-sessions-asks-remaining-46-us-attorneys-to-resign.html|accessdate=March 10, 2017|publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=March 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310215559/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/03/10/ag-sessions-asks-remaining-46-us-attorneys-to-resign.html|archive-date=March 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Trump also allowed [[Deirdre M. Daly]] and [[Richard S. Hartunian]] to remain in office for a period of several months until they completed 20 years of service at the Justice Department.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gerstein |first1=Josh |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2017/03/us-attorneys-dismissal-236009 |title=2 more U.S. attorneys win reprieves from dismissal order |website=[[Politico]] |date=March 13, 2017 |accessdate=March 13, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314015121/http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2017/03/us-attorneys-dismissal-236009 |archive-date=March 14, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Preet Bharara]] refused to resign and was fired.<ref name=\"Bharara\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Attorney Preet Bharara Says He Did No